{"type":"message","id":"d14223b0","parentId":"fe27c39d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T13:22:13.639Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This message is coming in as if it's from Ray (sender_label: \"Ray\"). But the conversation metadata shows it was sent by Jo (id:1616824689, username: jojo_naan). The message_id is 1667 and it's a reply to message 1666.\n\nThis is strange - the message appears to be FROM Ray (as the sender_label), but the Telegram metadata says it was from Jo. This could mean:\n\n1. Someone is sending a message that appears to come from Ray (via a Telegram bot that has Ray's username)\n2. This is a forwarded message that was sent through Ray's Telegram account\n3. OpenClaw is interpreting this as coming from Ray because the sender_label is \"Ray\" in the body\n\n\n4. The actual Telegram sender is Jo, so it's coming from Jo's account but the content itself is labeled as Ray's\n\nI should check the Telegram bot configuration to understand how this message is being routed and whether there's a bot associated with the Ray account that's forwarding these messages.\n\nThe message ID sequence is interesting - if this is 1667 and it's the latest, it means 1666 came just before, which could be from an OpenClaw agent or the user themselves. Given that Leo's Vegas V1 Alpha team and files have been deleted, and there's no active cron job for that signal format, this message is almost certainly being manually sent by Jo or someone with access to that Telegram bot.\n\nBut the sender_label showing as \"Ray\" is the real puzzle here - that's not Jo. I'm wondering if there's a Telegram bot configured where messages FROM a specific bot appear with that bot's name as the sender_label, and Jo is somehow sending FROM that bot rather than directly to Ray.\n\nActually, the simplest explanation is that Jo manually sent this Vegas V1 Alpha formatted message to Ray, and OpenClaw's routing is interpreting it as coming from Ray because it's addre